WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.729
<i>ARTHUR". In New York City, at 6am,</i>

00:02.840 --> 00:06.208
<i>the Wall Street Stock Exchange crashed.</i>

00:06.320 --> 00:09.244
<i>THOMAS". I told Michael on Friday
this was going to happen.</i>

00:09.360 --> 00:11.488
We were most definitely on board.

00:14.040 --> 00:16.361
But you have to listen
to the voices that you hear.

00:16.480 --> 00:18.209
<i>- (GUNSHOT)
- (HORSE NEIGHS)</i>

00:22.280 --> 00:24.726
My name is Mosley. Oswald Mosley.

00:24.840 --> 00:26.365
THOMAS: Yeah, I know who you are.

00:26.480 --> 00:28.369
You have come to my attention.

00:30.080 --> 00:32.924
Mr Shelby?
Mr Levitt from the London <i>Times.</i>

00:33.040 --> 00:35.930
<i>Ten</i> years <i>ago,</i> I <i>was a journalist
on the Birmingham Evening Mail.</i>

00:36.040 --> 00:37.849
Course, working in that city,

00:37.960 --> 00:39.962
it was impossible not to know your name.

00:40.080 --> 00:42.731
And your...reputation.

00:42.840 --> 00:45.889
What is your Tory newspaper
more afraid of?

00:46.000 --> 00:49.163
Is it evolution or revolution?

01:13.560 --> 01:15.403
(SIGHS)

01:18.800 --> 01:20.290
(GLASS RATTLES)

01:20.400 --> 01:22.289
(POURS LIQUID)

01:56.200 --> 01:59.044
(PHONE RINGS)

02:23.560 --> 02:26.006
(CROW CAWS)

02:52.440 --> 02:54.568
(CROW CAWS)

03:05.520 --> 03:08.364
(WIND HOWLS)

03:25.720 --> 03:28.769
(TICKING)

03:28.880 --> 03:32.487
(MUD SLOSHES)

04:11.840 --> 04:13.808
(SIGHS)

05:18.080 --> 05:19.650
(GROANS)

05:19.760 --> 05:23.367
DISTORTED CHILD'S VOICE:
Dad! There's a phone call for you!

05:28.760 --> 05:31.684
Dad! There's a phone call for you!

05:33.160 --> 05:34.207
THOMAS: Charlie!

05:35.720 --> 05:39.042
Charlie! Wait!

05:39.160 --> 05:40.366
Charlie!

05:56.280 --> 05:58.408
Giddy-up, horsey, giddy-up!

06:04.280 --> 06:08.205
- Dad, there's a phone call for you.
- Good boy.

06:08.320 --> 06:10.084
Good boy.

06:10.200 --> 06:12.168
Will you go back to the house?

06:12.280 --> 06:14.362
And, er, whoever's calling,

06:14.480 --> 06:17.006
the operator will have their number,

06:17.120 --> 06:19.088
and I'll call them back, eh?

06:19.200 --> 06:21.043
(CAR APPROACH ES)

06:22.520 --> 06:23.726
Oh, look, Charlie.

06:23.840 --> 06:25.524
You must have violin practice.

06:25.640 --> 06:27.051
It's Mrs Milligan.

06:27.160 --> 06:28.161
Go on.

06:29.480 --> 06:30.641
And, Charlie!

06:30.760 --> 06:33.161
Charlie, you play loudly.

06:33.280 --> 06:35.009
You might hear some bangs.

06:36.120 --> 06:37.406
Go on.

06:50.960 --> 06:52.485
(SIGHS)

07:03.800 --> 07:06.121
(VIOLIN PRACTICE IN DISTANCE)

08:29.880 --> 08:31.405
<i>OPERATOR: Mr Shelby?</i>

08:31.520 --> 08:33.602
Maggie, yeah, it's me.

08:33.720 --> 08:35.927
- Yes, Mr Shelby.
- I just missed a call.

08:36.039 --> 08:37.326
Where was it from?

08:37.440 --> 08:39.044
<i>Belfast.</i>

08:39.159 --> 08:42.482
Belfast. Where in Belfast?

08:42.600 --> 08:44.602
<i>Um, I'm not sure.</i>

08:44.720 --> 08:46.449
Do you have the number?

08:46.560 --> 08:47.971
Yeah.

08:50.440 --> 08:51.965
Yeah, can you put me through?

08:52.080 --> 08:54.811
(STATIC)

08:57.120 --> 08:59.043
(STATIC STOPS)

09:00.120 --> 09:01.281
<i>MICHAEL: Tommy, don't believe...</i>

09:06.920 --> 09:08.922
Mr Shelby.

09:09.040 --> 09:10.530
My name is Captain Swing,

09:10.640 --> 09:12.483
calling from the occupied Six Counties.

09:12.600 --> 09:15.080
And there are some people
from the other side

09:15.200 --> 09:18.522
of our neat little city
that want you dead.

09:18.640 --> 09:24.488
<i>You should also know that this boy,
this Michael, your kin,</i>

09:24.600 --> 09:28.207
was in his cabin
aboard the SS Monroe in Belfast dock,

09:28.320 --> 09:30.926
making deals with the very men
who want you dead.

09:31.040 --> 09:31.962
Tommy, they're lying!

09:32.080 --> 09:35.562
Now, if you want, we can put
a bullet in his head here and now...

09:36.640 --> 09:38.688
...or we can send him home,
and you can deal with him.

09:45.000 --> 09:46.604
Send him home.

09:47.880 --> 09:49.564
Very well, Mr Shelby.

09:49.680 --> 09:53.890
But be informed that this kin of yours
was talking to representatives

09:54.000 --> 09:57.163
from the County Tyrone and Glasgow UVF

09:57.280 --> 09:59.203
about how they'd divide up
the English racetracks

09:59.320 --> 10:02.881
- after they'd blown away your legs.
- Tommy, they're lying!

10:05.400 --> 10:06.481
And may I ask...

10:07.680 --> 10:09.523
...why you are doing me this favour?

10:12.800 --> 10:13.961
Because, Mr Shelby,

10:14.080 --> 10:16.890
we've been informed
by people at the very highest level

10:17.000 --> 10:19.844
that, since your conversion to socialism,

10:19.960 --> 10:22.406
you are now on the side of the angels.

10:22.520 --> 10:25.649
And angels can be useful to us.

10:27.360 --> 10:28.805
(LIN E 015.com N ECTS)

10:46.400 --> 10:47.640
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

10:47.760 --> 10:49.171
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

10:51.680 --> 10:52.920
Come.

11:01.240 --> 11:04.847
Mr Shelby, the violin teacher
wants to know what all those bangs were.

11:05.960 --> 11:07.291
Fireworks.

11:07.400 --> 11:09.050
Was trying them out for Saturday.

11:12.320 --> 11:15.085
You promised the doctor
not until after dark.

11:16.360 --> 11:18.203
Oh, it's pretty dark, Frances.

11:21.480 --> 11:22.925
Also,

11:23.040 --> 11:26.328
will Mrs Shelby and Ruby be home
for dinner tonight?

11:26.440 --> 11:27.726
I don't know.

11:37.120 --> 11:38.167
CHARLES: Dad?

11:39.240 --> 11:41.447
I've learned something this morning.

11:41.560 --> 11:42.971
Have you?

11:45.840 --> 11:47.080
So have I.

11:48.400 --> 11:49.765
And what have you learned, my boy?

11:52.520 --> 11:55.524
(SCRATCHY TUNE ON VIOLIN)

12:12.680 --> 12:15.809
Let's get this over with.
I've got a train to catch.

12:15.920 --> 12:17.809
Go get your train, Tom.
I can deal with this.

12:17.920 --> 12:18.921
Oi.

12:19.040 --> 12:21.725
- (come CLINK)
- Get it!

12:41.040 --> 12:42.849
Go home.

12:45.440 --> 12:46.805
Come here, you.

12:46.920 --> 12:49.048
Put this on.

12:49.160 --> 12:51.686
There you go.
Look at that, it looks great on you.

12:51.800 --> 12:53.484
Wrap up warm.

13:04.880 --> 13:06.609
Ah!

13:06.720 --> 13:07.881
Wake up.

13:09.160 --> 13:11.162
Rise and shine.

13:11.280 --> 13:12.281
What are you doing here?

13:12.400 --> 13:14.402
Wasting our fucking time on you.

13:18.800 --> 13:20.404
Sit down, Finn.

13:20.520 --> 13:22.568
Sit down.

13:29.560 --> 13:30.800
What do I have to do...

13:32.080 --> 13:34.208
...to make you fucking listen to me?

13:34.320 --> 13:37.324
You took a bullet.

13:37.440 --> 13:39.841
You've been running around the streets
with a fucking gun in your hand.

13:42.080 --> 13:43.570
Somebody has to.

13:46.160 --> 13:48.561
Finn, we've got people
for that kind of work.

13:48.680 --> 13:52.321
Soldiers. Captains and corporals.

13:52.440 --> 13:53.726
Well, then, what am I?

13:55.200 --> 13:56.326
"What am I?" Jesus Christ.

13:56.440 --> 13:59.603
Yeah, what am I, Tom, huh?

13:59.720 --> 14:01.484
I'm the brother you never got round to.

14:02.520 --> 14:05.000
You're a general, Finn.

14:05.120 --> 14:06.281
You understand?

14:06.400 --> 14:09.609
You're a fucking Shelby,
so you're a general.

14:09.720 --> 14:13.725
When did you last see a general
anywhere near the blood and the puke, eh?

14:15.080 --> 14:17.287
He's fucking right.

14:17.400 --> 14:19.164
That's what you are.

14:19.280 --> 14:21.681
So on your feet, soldier.

14:21.800 --> 14:23.404
Come on, on your feet.

14:23.520 --> 14:26.126
I thought you just said I was a general.

14:26.240 --> 14:27.890
I did just say you were.

14:28.000 --> 14:29.365
So get on your fucking feet!

14:29.480 --> 14:31.164
Arthur...

14:31.280 --> 14:33.567
(SIGHS) Finn. Finn.

14:33.680 --> 14:34.806
Look at this.

14:34.920 --> 14:38.925
This is the bullet
that Aberama Gold cut from you.

14:39.040 --> 14:41.486
First and last.

14:42.880 --> 14:45.360
First and last.

14:50.400 --> 14:51.686
Don't lose it.

14:52.960 --> 14:55.691
Go and clean up, put some clothes on.

14:55.800 --> 14:57.450
A nice suit.

14:57.560 --> 14:59.961
I've got some trouble
that'll keep you out of trouble.

15:01.640 --> 15:04.086
- Oh, and, erm, Tom...
- Yeah?

15:04.200 --> 15:05.611
...while you're here,

15:05.720 --> 15:07.961
erm, I've met this girl

15:08.080 --> 15:10.208
- and I'd like to get married.
- Fuck off. Go, get dressed.

15:10.320 --> 15:11.321
Go on, move.

15:11.440 --> 15:12.680
<i>GM!</i>

15:12.800 --> 15:14.848
Finn, this girl you're trying to impress,

15:14.960 --> 15:16.371
tell me about her.

15:17.400 --> 15:18.811
She likes the life.

15:18.920 --> 15:21.048
She likes the life, eh?

15:21.160 --> 15:22.491
Well, find one that hates it.

15:22.600 --> 15:25.649
Look at him, that's what he did.
Now he's chairman of the board.

15:28.320 --> 15:29.685
Go on. Hurry up.

15:30.800 --> 15:31.847
Arthur?

15:31.960 --> 15:35.521
Lizzie and Ruby, are they still at yours?

15:38.480 --> 15:40.448
Yes, Tom, they're still there.

15:40.560 --> 15:43.086
She's coming home today, she said, so...

15:43.200 --> 15:44.611
...she'll be home later.

15:45.680 --> 15:48.365
Hm. Has she been talking about me?

15:48.480 --> 15:51.324
I mean, they talk a lot,
you know what women are like.

15:51.440 --> 15:54.330
The kitchen and, you know,
kids running around.

15:54.440 --> 15:56.442
I...I don't pay 'em no mind, Tom.

15:56.560 --> 15:58.449
- I don't listen to 'em 'alf the time.
- Yeah.

15:59.680 --> 16:01.125
Well, everything she says is true.

16:05.280 --> 16:06.566
Well...

16:08.920 --> 16:10.126
...you like the life, Tommy.

16:10.240 --> 16:12.208
I don't like the fucking life.

16:12.320 --> 16:14.049
I don't like the fucking life,

16:14.160 --> 16:16.447
I don't like
that Michael is coming back today.

16:19.920 --> 16:22.127
Train arrives from Liverpool at three.

16:22.240 --> 16:23.526
Polly will be there.

16:23.640 --> 16:24.766
Take a weapon.

16:25.880 --> 16:28.087
Tell Moss to clear the station of coppers.

16:28.200 --> 16:29.440
You hear me?

16:29.560 --> 16:30.607
Yes, sir.

16:32.960 --> 16:34.769
Hey, Tommy.

16:36.480 --> 16:38.448
I heard 'em say one thing, though.

16:39.720 --> 16:42.963
Just talking, you know,
they were saying that, er,

16:43.080 --> 16:46.562
you...you don't sleep or something.

16:46.680 --> 16:48.170
You can't sleep.

16:50.240 --> 16:53.403
When I do sleep, I dream.

16:54.680 --> 16:58.480
And in my dream,
someone wants my crown.

16:58.600 --> 17:00.967
I think it might be Michael.

17:02.080 --> 17:03.923
Call me at three.

17:10.920 --> 17:13.048
Arthur, I'm gonna put
that bullet on a necklace

17:13.160 --> 17:14.366
and wear it as a reminder.

17:15.319 --> 17:16.890
Arthur?

17:17.000 --> 17:19.367
- I heard you.
- You got trouble for me, then?

17:19.480 --> 17:20.970
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

17:33.560 --> 17:34.925
(GRUNTS)

17:36.000 --> 17:38.651
Mr Shelby,
the...the police are here to see you.

17:38.760 --> 17:40.171
Police aren't allowed in here.

17:40.280 --> 17:43.284
Er, he's not in uniform
and said it's very unofficial.

17:45.240 --> 17:46.366
(DOOR CLOSES)

17:48.800 --> 17:51.326
Afternoon. Someone get you some tea?

17:51.440 --> 17:52.771
No, I'm fine, Mr Shelby.

17:52.880 --> 17:54.166
- This won't take long.
- Good.

17:55.240 --> 17:57.129
You've got five minutes.

17:57.240 --> 18:01.689
Mr Shelby,
there was a shooting two days ago.

18:01.800 --> 18:03.529
A man died.

18:03.640 --> 18:05.051
It was a murder.

18:07.160 --> 18:08.207
In Maida Vale.

18:09.640 --> 18:10.721
Of all places.

18:13.520 --> 18:15.329
- His name was Levitt.
- Uh-huh.

18:18.000 --> 18:19.525
He was a journalist.

18:30.360 --> 18:33.364
The night before he was shot,
he came here to see you.

18:33.480 --> 18:37.849
We found a Commons pass
and your name in his diary.

18:37.960 --> 18:42.363
I was wondering
what his business here was.

18:43.680 --> 18:44.841
And I'm wondering...

18:46.000 --> 18:47.968
...what your business here is.

18:49.840 --> 18:52.605
According to his diary,
you knew him from Birmingham.

18:52.720 --> 18:53.960
What's your name?

18:55.240 --> 18:56.287
Stacker.

18:56.400 --> 18:58.209
Stacker. OK.

19:00.640 --> 19:03.803
Mr Shelby, Mr Levitt was a queer.

19:03.920 --> 19:05.922
Some may think
it was one of his queer friends...

19:06.040 --> 19:07.610
Mr Stacker,

19:07.720 --> 19:11.281
I get the feeling that,
with a little provocation,

19:11.400 --> 19:13.243
you could be very persistent.

19:13.360 --> 19:15.567
Only within my remit.

19:15.680 --> 19:17.967
Well, your Chief Constable Wyatt,

19:18.080 --> 19:21.562
he has clear views about persistence,
which he has shared with me.

19:21.680 --> 19:22.727
Mr Shelby...

19:22.840 --> 19:26.481
He likes persistence, as do I.
And thoroughness.

19:26.600 --> 19:27.840
But not frivolity.

19:29.440 --> 19:35.561
A man who walks in the park with other men
dies in Maida Vale.

19:35.680 --> 19:37.808
And you come to me?

19:37.920 --> 19:40.730
As well as his diary,
we have his notebook.

19:40.840 --> 19:43.241
(CLOCK CHIMES)

19:43.360 --> 19:46.045
Your time's up, Mr Stacker.

19:55.320 --> 19:56.560
Thank you.

19:59.640 --> 20:02.086
(DOOR CLOSES)

20:36.600 --> 20:37.726
Hello, Mum.

20:40.360 --> 20:41.930
This is Gina.

20:43.040 --> 20:44.530
Gina Gray.

20:46.240 --> 20:48.083
The captain married us on board.

20:51.080 --> 20:52.730
She's my wife, Mum. At least look at her.

20:52.840 --> 20:56.561
Tommy said to ask you
to tell me the truth.

20:57.640 --> 21:00.246
We've been travelling for 15 days,
Mrs Gray.

21:00.360 --> 21:01.771
Maybe we could talk about this
at another time.

21:01.880 --> 21:02.802
Yes.

21:02.920 --> 21:04.206
Let's go home and we can talk.

21:04.320 --> 21:08.689
You have no home
until you tell me the truth.

21:08.800 --> 21:10.245
Here?

21:10.360 --> 21:12.283
Yeah.

21:14.920 --> 21:16.285
ARTHUR: Michael!

21:19.080 --> 21:20.445
Hello, love.

21:22.000 --> 21:25.004
Welcome to Birmingham, eh?

21:26.360 --> 21:28.169
Michael?

21:29.640 --> 21:30.846
OK.

21:33.080 --> 21:35.208
Our ship docked at Belfast.

21:35.320 --> 21:36.924
I was then taken off the ship by two men.

21:37.040 --> 21:37.962
At gunpoint.

21:38.080 --> 21:40.128
I'm speaking to my son.

21:40.240 --> 21:41.401
Fuck you.

21:42.920 --> 21:44.604
Fuck you too, Arthur.

21:44.720 --> 21:49.282
This is my fucking wife.
I bring her home... To this?

21:52.080 --> 21:54.367
Come on, Gina.

21:57.600 --> 22:00.171
Well, where are you going now, eh? Hmm?

22:00.280 --> 22:02.009
Introduce me at least.

22:02.120 --> 22:04.327
- Excuse me.
- Look at this.

22:04.440 --> 22:06.363
Look at this.

22:06.480 --> 22:08.403
This is it, Gina.

22:08.520 --> 22:11.683
This is my fucking people.

22:11.800 --> 22:13.962
Do you want to know the truth, Arthur?

22:14.080 --> 22:15.445
Do you want to know the truth, Mum?

22:16.640 --> 22:22.044
I did not betray my fucking family!

22:23.320 --> 22:25.402
Now, Mum...

22:26.760 --> 22:27.886
...I want to go home.

22:29.680 --> 22:32.604
POLLY: I've booked you a suite
at the Midland Hotel.

22:34.080 --> 22:36.447
MICHAEL:
Was that Tommy's orders, then, was it?

22:36.560 --> 22:39.723
See, the Midland Hotel
is Tommy's little kingdom.

22:41.160 --> 22:44.130
Where all the porters keep an eye,

22:44.240 --> 22:47.722
where all the telephone exchange girls
are reporting on my calls.

22:47.840 --> 22:54.121
Yeah, well, why don't you think of it
like, er, quarantine, Michael, eh?

22:54.240 --> 22:57.722
We'll treat you like a fucking dog, hmm?

22:59.400 --> 23:00.890
Smelly one.

23:01.000 --> 23:02.286
Stinking one.

23:03.280 --> 23:08.002
Until we know you're clean, hmm?

23:08.120 --> 23:10.088
Fuck you, Arthur.

23:10.200 --> 23:12.009
Stand aside, Arthur.

23:12.120 --> 23:13.690
No, Poll.

23:21.480 --> 23:22.606
Come on, baby.

23:22.720 --> 23:24.449
Forget about 'em.

23:24.560 --> 23:27.643
Go and phone Tommy, tell him.

23:27.760 --> 23:30.491
Polly says Michael's telling the truth.

23:30.600 --> 23:33.126
GINA: It's all right. Forget about 'em.

23:33.240 --> 23:34.241
All right, Poll.

23:36.960 --> 23:38.883
Nice coat.

23:39.000 --> 23:40.809
What are you like? Camel, right?

23:43.640 --> 23:44.641
Oh.

23:46.400 --> 23:50.689
Welcome to the family, Gina Gray.

23:53.760 --> 23:57.560
THOMAS: I applaud the attempt by Mr Rowley
in the Education Bill

23:57.680 --> 24:00.490
to raise the school leaving age to 15.

24:00.600 --> 24:02.364
I also support...

24:18.000 --> 24:20.526
...as regards means-testing of any kind,

24:20.640 --> 24:22.244
- we are the people...
- MEMBERS: Yeah!

24:22.360 --> 24:25.330
- ...we've had enough.
- MEMBERS: Yeah!

24:25.440 --> 24:28.444
"We are the people,
and we've had enough."

24:28.560 --> 24:30.289
I move in favour of the amendment.

24:46.040 --> 24:47.246
Mr Shelby.

24:48.920 --> 24:52.322
I must say,
you sing like a songbird in the House.

24:54.000 --> 24:56.128
And who is this pretty finch?

24:56.240 --> 24:57.162
My sister.

24:57.280 --> 24:58.327
Who's pregnant.

24:58.440 --> 24:59.601
And dangerous.

24:59.720 --> 25:02.291
- (CLEARS HIS THROAT)
- Oh, we adore dangerous.

25:02.400 --> 25:03.811
Who's <i>we?</i>

25:03.920 --> 25:06.241
It's a collective noun,

25:06.360 --> 25:10.524
in this case describing a group of people
who are impatient and young and,

25:10.640 --> 25:13.086
as I have said, adore dangerous.

25:14.800 --> 25:18.122
Mr Shelby, you had a horse of that name.

25:20.280 --> 25:21.645
Whiskey. Irish.

25:21.760 --> 25:24.161
Give him one from my bottle.

25:24.280 --> 25:26.601
And one for myself.
In fact, bring the bottle.

25:27.760 --> 25:28.727
And the lady?

25:28.840 --> 25:30.365
Isn't thirsty.

25:30.480 --> 25:32.130
How do you know about the horse?

25:34.000 --> 25:36.048
We have a mutual acquaintance.

25:37.120 --> 25:38.246
May Carleton.

25:38.360 --> 25:42.160
When I asked about you, she said,
"Oh, my goodness, where do I begin?"

25:43.560 --> 25:45.961
And why were you asking after me?

25:46.080 --> 25:48.526
Because, as I have said,

25:48.640 --> 25:50.483
I adore dangerous.

25:51.560 --> 25:53.244
And where did she begin?

25:53.360 --> 25:56.284
You know, I was rather hoping
we might have this meeting alone.

25:56.400 --> 25:58.846
My sister is my political adviser.

25:58.960 --> 26:02.328
And my advice just now was,
"Don't meet Mr Mosley."

26:02.440 --> 26:04.249
Because I am dangerous?

26:04.360 --> 26:06.249
No.

26:06.360 --> 26:09.011
What is it you are impatient for,
Mr Mosley?

26:09.120 --> 26:12.841
I'm impatient for my fucking whiskey.

26:15.400 --> 26:16.640
Bennett!

26:18.920 --> 26:20.922
May Carleton spoke about you

26:21.040 --> 26:24.806
the way I imagine one might
about a party they barely remember,

26:24.920 --> 26:27.730
where you crash the car
into the dovecote

26:27.840 --> 26:31.208
and live on champagne and cocaine
for three whole days.

26:31.320 --> 26:32.845
You know, that kind of party.

26:32.960 --> 26:35.008
Only three days?

26:36.320 --> 26:37.446
Hmm.

26:41.400 --> 26:44.643
My sister advised against meeting you

26:44.760 --> 26:49.209
because it appears
you are moving away from the party...

26:50.720 --> 26:52.802
...in a different direction.

26:52.920 --> 26:55.127
And which direction is that?

26:55.240 --> 26:57.368
Towards fascism.

26:57.480 --> 27:01.644
"We are the people,
and we have had enough."

27:03.560 --> 27:05.289
I thought that was excellent.

27:06.560 --> 27:09.928
In which direction are you heading,
Mr Shelby?

27:10.040 --> 27:12.771
I am my own revolution.

27:12.880 --> 27:15.565
And you prefer Irish to Scotch.

27:17.480 --> 27:18.720
As do I.

27:18.840 --> 27:22.731
Like all things regarding Ireland,
it is...complex.

27:22.840 --> 27:23.887
Yes?

27:31.160 --> 27:32.810
0h!

27:33.880 --> 27:36.804
Where do you stand
on the Irish question, Mr Shelby?

27:36.920 --> 27:39.651
Never been asked it.

27:39.760 --> 27:41.967
Then perhaps it's time you were.

27:42.080 --> 27:46.881
Tommy, I am the people,
and I have had enough.

27:47.000 --> 27:49.571
We are looking for someone
to begin a dialogue...

27:49.680 --> 27:51.967
...with certain elements in Belfast

27:52.080 --> 27:54.924
with whom
we don't officially have any dealings.

27:55.040 --> 27:58.487
I'll be too busy singing in the House.

27:58.600 --> 28:00.728
It would involve a promotion.

28:02.360 --> 28:05.762
Junior Minister to the Duchy of Lancaster.

28:06.840 --> 28:08.569
Birmingham is my concern.

28:08.680 --> 28:13.641
Ireland bores me.
Thanks for the whiskey, Mr Mosley.

28:15.160 --> 28:16.730
(CLEARS HIS THROAT)

28:20.600 --> 28:22.409
Hmm.

28:22.520 --> 28:24.648
What the fuck was that about?

28:24.760 --> 28:27.809
Ireland. It's been Ireland's day
all fucking day long.

28:27.920 --> 28:28.842
What do you mean?

28:28.960 --> 28:32.567
Ada, go home and start calling
anyone who had dealings

28:32.680 --> 28:35.160
with Shelby Company Limited
while you were in Boston.

28:35.280 --> 28:36.441
Ask them about Michael.

28:38.200 --> 28:40.202
Ask them whatabout him?

28:40.320 --> 28:42.607
Who he's been seeing,
who he's been meeting,

28:42.720 --> 28:45.405
- what deals he's made.
- Why?

28:45.520 --> 28:50.082
Ask 'em especially about people
he's met from Glasgow or Belfast.

28:50.200 --> 28:53.568
Tommy,
why don't you come back with me, eh?

28:53.680 --> 28:55.569
You can play chess with Karl.

28:55.680 --> 28:57.523
I'll make some calls,
you can listen in.

28:57.640 --> 28:58.607
Drive home tomorrow.

28:58.720 --> 29:01.326
That bastard starts talking
about Irish whiskey.

29:01.440 --> 29:02.680
The fuck does he know? Eh?

29:02.800 --> 29:05.644
More than me, Tommy.
What are you talking about?

29:05.760 --> 29:08.923
I'm talking about an empty chair, Ada.

29:09.040 --> 29:11.247
My chair. My throne.

29:11.360 --> 29:12.930
People thinking I'm gonna fall,

29:13.040 --> 29:15.441
they start behaving
in a different way around you.

29:15.560 --> 29:16.925
Who thinks that?

29:17.040 --> 29:19.202
They start to circle.

29:19.320 --> 29:21.322
Who's going to take the throne, eh?

29:21.440 --> 29:23.761
Linda, she wants some for Arthur,

29:23.880 --> 29:26.326
Aberama Gold, people in the north,
Michael...

29:26.440 --> 29:28.602
(CLEARS HIS THROAT)

29:31.040 --> 29:34.203
just go home, make some calls.

29:34.320 --> 29:36.209
Protestants are coming, I think.

29:36.320 --> 29:38.322
I need to get back to Birmingham.

29:40.000 --> 29:41.570
(SIGHS)

29:51.240 --> 29:52.844
Polly.

29:52.960 --> 29:54.450
Are you armed?

29:55.800 --> 29:57.723
Yeah.

29:57.840 --> 29:59.046
Yeah.

29:59.160 --> 30:01.481
Would you please consider
putting your weapons behind the bar

30:01.600 --> 30:04.001
in case feelings begin to run high?

30:04.120 --> 30:05.690
Behind the bar, Poll, eh?

30:06.920 --> 30:08.729
Behind my own bar, yeah?

30:15.600 --> 30:16.647
I prefer it there.

30:19.320 --> 30:21.049
Thomas?

30:29.280 --> 30:31.044
I had a dream...

30:31.160 --> 30:34.607
...about a black cat last night, Poll.

30:36.480 --> 30:39.927
A black cat dream
means there is a traitor close by.

30:40.040 --> 30:41.690
It was you who taught me that.

30:41.800 --> 30:44.201
Black cat can mean lots of things.

30:44.320 --> 30:46.766
Can mean you're hurting yourself.

30:46.880 --> 30:48.006
Betraying yourself.

30:49.480 --> 30:51.687
Are you seeing things, Thomas?

30:54.080 --> 30:55.206
Yes, I am.

30:55.320 --> 30:56.924
(CAR APPROACH ES)

30:57.040 --> 30:59.441
Yes, I am. Very clearly.

31:01.160 --> 31:02.969
Coming from every fucking direction.

31:04.960 --> 31:06.769
(CAR ENGINE STOPS)

31:07.840 --> 31:09.330
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

31:11.640 --> 31:13.210
(BAR DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

31:17.240 --> 31:18.321
Tommy.

31:19.800 --> 31:21.689
I'd like to introduce you to my wife.

31:23.760 --> 31:26.240
I would also like to, er, say something.

31:26.360 --> 31:28.886
- Sit down, Michael.
- I betrayed you.

31:29.000 --> 31:31.651
- Michael.
- But only in my heart.

31:31.760 --> 31:33.444
There was a time,

31:33.560 --> 31:35.005
in America,

31:35.120 --> 31:37.441
and there was a lot of money in that bank.

31:37.560 --> 31:39.688
And I wondered
if I could...I could leave,

31:39.800 --> 31:41.723
move to California.

31:41.840 --> 31:43.842
Someone said I should invest in pictures.

31:45.120 --> 31:46.246
Hollywood.

31:47.480 --> 31:48.925
But Gina stopped me.

31:50.240 --> 31:53.210
- Gina said...
- I told you to sit down, Michael.

32:01.960 --> 32:03.007
Now, tell me...

32:04.760 --> 32:06.888
...what happened on that ship

32:07.000 --> 32:08.729
in Belfast harbour.

32:11.680 --> 32:14.923
On the journey back from New York,
we got married.

32:15.040 --> 32:16.804
But we needed to find a witness.

32:16.920 --> 32:18.126
A purser.

32:18.240 --> 32:19.651
He was from Belfast.

32:19.760 --> 32:20.841
We got friendly.

32:20.960 --> 32:22.166
What happened when the ship docked?

32:24.600 --> 32:29.128
This purser had friends who ran
a whiskey distillery in County Tyrone.

32:29.240 --> 32:31.607
They wanted a way
of getting their stuff into America.

32:31.720 --> 32:34.371
So I said, "OK, invite them aboard."

32:34.480 --> 32:37.768
When they came in, I realised
that they didn't make whiskey.

32:37.880 --> 32:39.723
They were Scottish. From Glasgow.

32:39.840 --> 32:42.411
Couldn't understood
a fucking word they were saying.

32:42.520 --> 32:45.046
They started swearing,

32:45.160 --> 32:46.764
so I asked Gina to leave.

32:47.840 --> 32:50.764
That was when they started talking
about you, Tom.

32:50.880 --> 32:54.362
They said that Tommy Shelby
was a spent force,

32:54.480 --> 32:56.687
that politics had got to him...

32:58.200 --> 33:00.009
...that he was spent in the head,

33:00.120 --> 33:02.691
that now was a good time to move in

33:02.800 --> 33:04.802
and did I want to be part of it.

33:04.920 --> 33:07.491
They knew about the money we lost
in America.

33:07.600 --> 33:09.125
They said that you were going to blame me.

33:09.240 --> 33:11.607
That you had a bullet with my name on it.

33:14.080 --> 33:15.570
What did you say, Michael?

33:15.680 --> 33:17.011
I didn't have time to say anything.

33:18.240 --> 33:20.049
Coppers came on board.

33:20.160 --> 33:21.446
Well, I thought they were coppers.

33:21.560 --> 33:22.721
They, er...

33:24.200 --> 33:25.770
They were IRA.

33:25.880 --> 33:27.041
Exactly.

33:32.880 --> 33:35.804
And the first men from Glasgow?

33:37.600 --> 33:42.640
The IRA commander said the men
from Glasgow were called Billy Boys.

33:43.640 --> 33:45.051
Fucking Billy Boys.

33:45.160 --> 33:47.208
I don't know who the fuck Billy Boys are.

33:47.320 --> 33:53.043
They run every man in every coalmine,
on every shipyard east of Glasgow.

33:53.160 --> 33:57.131
Ties with Belfast, UVF.

33:57.240 --> 33:59.083
Protestant razor gang.

33:59.200 --> 34:02.044
They also dabble in politics.

34:02.160 --> 34:06.484
You know, muscle for fascist rallies.

34:06.600 --> 34:09.284
But you did no deal, Michael?

34:09.400 --> 34:11.402
You didn't even know who they were?

34:11.520 --> 34:14.251
I was too busy looking forward
to giving you the good news.

34:15.920 --> 34:19.686
The reason Gina and I got married
on the ship was because Gina is pregnant.

34:21.159 --> 34:23.049
You're going to be a grandmother.

34:31.480 --> 34:32.766
OK, Michael.

34:34.360 --> 34:35.725
I believe you.

34:35.840 --> 34:37.170
Welcome home.

34:38.440 --> 34:39.521
Congratulations.

34:40.679 --> 34:42.648
Just remember...

34:42.760 --> 34:47.243
Your unborn child has witnessed
what you said.

34:47.360 --> 34:49.806
- Thomas!
- And it will be born according to...

34:49.920 --> 34:50.920
You fuck!

34:51.040 --> 34:54.408
Where the fuck are you going, hmm?

34:54.520 --> 34:56.443
Are you fucking mad, hmm?

34:58.920 --> 35:03.926
- You are free to fucking leave, Michael.
- You fucking bastard.

35:04.040 --> 35:06.247
But you're not free, Michael, are you?

35:07.960 --> 35:10.088
You lost this company a lot of money.

35:10.200 --> 35:11.531
I told you to sell...

35:13.360 --> 35:14.691
...but you held on,

35:14.800 --> 35:19.522
and now I want you to pay me back
what you owe me.

35:19.640 --> 35:23.804
There is work you can do,
there are risks you can take.

35:23.920 --> 35:25.843
We were close before.

35:25.960 --> 35:27.803
Now I want you closer still.

35:30.120 --> 35:32.168
Michael, honey.

35:33.840 --> 35:35.205
Look at your cousin.

35:36.440 --> 35:37.805
He's in trouble, huh?

35:39.240 --> 35:40.571
He needs you.

35:43.360 --> 35:45.283
Come on, baby, let's go.

36:10.040 --> 36:11.610
Fucking cheek of her, eh?

36:13.560 --> 36:15.642
Mad Dog jimmY-

36:15.760 --> 36:17.842
Coming south.

36:22.600 --> 36:24.125
Not so mad any more.

36:24.240 --> 36:26.288
He's got friends in high places
these days.

36:29.440 --> 36:31.602
Black cat dream is never wrong, brother.

36:42.880 --> 36:45.042
(HORSE NEIGHS)

37:19.600 --> 37:21.011
(GUNSHOT)

37:21.120 --> 37:23.771
(GROANS)

37:23.880 --> 37:28.522
# Hello, hello, we are the Billy Boys

37:28.640 --> 37:32.361
# Hello, hello, we are the Billy Boys

37:32.480 --> 37:36.929
# We're up to our knees in Fenian blood
Surrender or you'll die

37:37.040 --> 37:40.840
# We are the Brigton Derry Billy Boys. #

37:43.880 --> 37:46.201
Drop the peashooter, son.

37:50.800 --> 37:55.124
A broken broom stops
all Gypsy curses, Mr Gold.

37:55.240 --> 37:58.608
Ah! (GROANS)

37:58.720 --> 37:59.960
(COUGHS)

38:00.080 --> 38:01.809
Who the fuck are you?

38:01.920 --> 38:03.809
Did you not hear my song?

38:03.920 --> 38:07.447
These gentlemen are the Billy Boys.

38:10.680 --> 38:12.409
And me?

38:16.080 --> 38:17.206
I'mjimmy.

38:17.320 --> 38:20.005
Ah, fuck, fuck.

38:20.120 --> 38:21.326
Good.

38:21.440 --> 38:23.920
Mouth broke, so you can't talk.

38:24.040 --> 38:26.520
But you don't need to.

38:26.640 --> 38:29.371
Your body will be the lesson.

38:30.560 --> 38:35.691
You work in a particular capacity
for Mr Thomas Shelby, OBE.

38:35.800 --> 38:37.131
Am I right?

38:43.920 --> 38:45.046
I heard you're a fighter.

38:47.040 --> 38:48.041
The best.

38:49.800 --> 38:52.406
But your fighting days are over.

38:52.520 --> 38:54.887
(GROANS)

38:55.000 --> 38:58.607
Because I need Mr Shelby to understand...

38:58.720 --> 39:02.008
...that his best...

39:02.120 --> 39:06.444
...is not...good enough.

39:06.560 --> 39:10.042
(MUFFLED SCREAMS)

39:13.920 --> 39:15.570
(MUFFLED SCREAMS)

39:41.720 --> 39:43.290
(MUFFLED SCREAMS)

39:48.120 --> 39:49.645
(GROANS)

39:57.280 --> 39:58.281
Bonnie!

39:59.560 --> 40:01.881
Farewell, fighter boy. You died well.

40:03.240 --> 40:04.446
(HORSE NEIGHS)

40:06.240 --> 40:07.446
(LABOURED BREATHING)

40:09.000 --> 40:10.968
(WHEEZES)

40:12.320 --> 40:14.402
(SOBS) Bonnie...

40:14.520 --> 40:16.124
Bonnie!

40:29.920 --> 40:33.402
Tell Tommy Shelby
it's time to fucking share.

40:35.640 --> 40:38.564
We'll take all the tracks out
as far as Nottingham.

40:38.680 --> 40:40.523
We'll take Cheltenham as well.

40:42.000 --> 40:46.085
Otherwise, it will be Thomas Shelby
who's crucified,

40:46.200 --> 40:48.806
and there will be no resurrection.

40:48.920 --> 40:50.888
(GROANS)

40:51.000 --> 40:52.331
(COUGHS)

40:52.440 --> 40:54.124
Come on, boys.

41:09.600 --> 41:11.921
(WHEEZES)

41:12.040 --> 41:14.566
<i>($055)</i>

41:14.880 --> 41:16.086
(SINGING INSIDE PUB)

41:19.000 --> 41:20.968
# But when you're crying

41:21.080 --> 41:27.440
# You bring out the rain
So stop your crying... #

41:27.560 --> 41:28.686
(MUSIC STOPS)

41:38.800 --> 41:41.724
Ladies and gentlemen, I'm just going to
take a short break. Thank you.

41:43.120 --> 41:44.963
Yeah. Good man.

41:51.720 --> 41:56.567
Beautiful, Billy, beautiful.
Really nice. Really nice.

42:00.920 --> 42:04.242
Really meaningful, you know?
A heartfelt song.

42:04.360 --> 42:07.091
I like it. I really do.

42:07.200 --> 42:11.285
Boys, this here is Billy Grade.

42:12.520 --> 42:14.010
Man I was telling you about, son.

42:16.120 --> 42:18.441
- Billy, this here's my kid brother, Finn.
- Hey.

42:19.880 --> 42:22.770
Have a drink, Billy.

42:22.880 --> 42:24.166
I can't, my voice is...

42:24.280 --> 42:26.601
Drink, Bill.

42:26.720 --> 42:27.960
Yeah.

42:29.080 --> 42:30.241
Yeah.

42:35.400 --> 42:37.243
You boys won't remember...

42:38.360 --> 42:42.251
...but I remember when Billy here
made a living on the football pitch.

42:42.360 --> 42:43.282
(LAUGHS)

42:43.400 --> 42:45.880
Oh, yeah, that was a long time ago,
Mr Shelby.

42:46.000 --> 42:47.525
- Yeah, what a left foot, eh?
- Yeah.

42:47.640 --> 42:48.971
(BOTH LAUGH)

42:49.080 --> 42:53.961
And then what? Manager, right? Hmm?

42:54.080 --> 42:56.651
Well, yeah, and now I'm a singer.

42:56.760 --> 42:57.921
Are you?

42:59.000 --> 43:03.927
Every football team in England
knows Billy Grade.

43:04.040 --> 43:07.806
And he knows a few people, too.
Don't you, Bill, eh? Hmm?

43:07.920 --> 43:10.161
- One or two.
- Useful.

43:11.320 --> 43:13.687
Very useful.

43:13.800 --> 43:15.802
But what do you do, Bill, eh?

43:15.920 --> 43:17.684
Hmm?

43:17.800 --> 43:22.283
You're in here, singing -
or whatever the fuck you call it -

43:22.400 --> 43:25.643
in shit-hole pubs in Birmingham.

43:25.760 --> 43:28.491
(TUT5)

43:28.600 --> 43:30.887
It's no way to make a living, boys.

43:31.960 --> 43:34.167
- Degrading.
- I love it.

43:34.280 --> 43:36.442
I really do, I love it.

43:37.600 --> 43:40.809
And thank you, by the way,
for inviting me here tonight.

43:40.920 --> 43:42.490
I really appreciate it,
so thank you very much.

43:42.600 --> 43:44.045
Don't thank me.

43:44.160 --> 43:46.083
I didn't invite you here to sing.

43:48.200 --> 43:52.603
If I wanted to listen to music,
I'd buy an Aljolson record. Hmm?

43:52.720 --> 43:54.882
That's what I'd do.

43:55.000 --> 43:57.321
Real singer, you know?

43:57.440 --> 43:58.930
Melody.

43:59.040 --> 44:00.849
Tune.

44:02.920 --> 44:05.651
So what is it that you want...exactly?

44:09.320 --> 44:13.166
Finn will explain
the nature of my proposition.

44:14.720 --> 44:16.802
You'll listen to him, won't you, Bill, eh?

44:16.920 --> 44:19.651
- You'll be attentive, won't you?
- Yeah, of course, course.

44:19.760 --> 44:20.682
Because Isiah here,

44:20.800 --> 44:24.122
he'll show you the fucking consequences
if you don't.

44:26.600 --> 44:27.840
All right?

44:30.920 --> 44:33.207
I'll leave you with the bottle, hmm?

44:47.280 --> 44:49.282
What proposition?

44:49.400 --> 44:52.324
Right, what I want from you, Billy,

44:52.440 --> 44:57.162
is for you to write down
a name and a number

44:57.280 --> 44:59.931
next to every one of those football teams,
yeah?

45:00.040 --> 45:01.724
- Why?
- Why?

45:01.840 --> 45:03.808
People like to bet on those kind of things
these days.

45:03.920 --> 45:06.048
- We are a gambling enterprise.
- I know who you are.

45:06.160 --> 45:09.926
To fix a horse race,
you give the outsider a bit of cocaine.

45:10.040 --> 45:11.804
- Jesus!
- To fix a football match,

45:11.920 --> 45:14.287
you give the goalkeeper Â£20.

45:25.680 --> 45:28.570
You're a Peaky Blinder now, Billy.

45:28.680 --> 45:29.841
Hmm?

45:38.000 --> 45:40.002
What have you got there?

45:41.560 --> 45:42.891
I've written a letter.

45:43.000 --> 45:44.411
Oh.

45:47.520 --> 45:48.885
Who for?

45:49.000 --> 45:50.764
For you.

45:50.880 --> 45:52.928
And Lizzie's written one to Tommy.

45:55.760 --> 45:57.000
Well...

45:58.120 --> 45:59.451
...can I read it?

45:59.560 --> 46:00.971
It's not finished yet.

46:02.280 --> 46:04.442
I'm getting rid of the parts
I wrote when I was drunk.

46:06.160 --> 46:08.083
By the way, I've stopped drinking.

46:08.200 --> 46:11.044
And your bottles of snow
I poured down the lavatory.

46:12.560 --> 46:14.324
When I was drunk, I was too hard on you.

46:14.440 --> 46:15.965
It's...it's not your fault.

46:21.160 --> 46:22.525
So...

46:24.680 --> 46:26.444
That letter's about me, is it?

46:26.560 --> 46:27.641
Yeah.

46:28.920 --> 46:30.729
- Hmm.
- And about me.

46:31.960 --> 46:33.883
About the future. About the company.

46:35.920 --> 46:37.001
Lizzie and I...

46:37.120 --> 46:40.249
Sat here and made things worse
the last few hours, hmm?

46:40.360 --> 46:42.362
Yeah, and we've come up with a plan.

46:42.480 --> 46:44.528
Oh, you've come up with a plan, eh?

46:44.640 --> 46:47.246
Lizzie says Tommy won't live
two more years if he carries on like this.

46:47.360 --> 46:48.282
He's gone too far.

46:48.400 --> 46:49.970
Is that what Lizzie says, hmm?

46:50.080 --> 46:51.241
Really now?

46:51.360 --> 46:54.011
Well, how far has he gone, hmm, Linda?
How far?

46:54.120 --> 46:56.327
He's lost all the legitimate money
in America.

46:56.440 --> 46:58.681
No. No, that was Michael.

46:58.800 --> 47:01.690
He's fixing races. He's fixing football.

47:01.800 --> 47:04.724
Following the financial crisis,
the Shelby Company Limited

47:04.840 --> 47:08.049
has to find other sources of cash income.

47:08.160 --> 47:09.844
Tommy went into Chinatown.

47:09.960 --> 47:13.442
He's selling out the Communists
to the British intelligence.

47:13.560 --> 47:16.325
And all the time, every day,
he gets more and more famous.

47:16.440 --> 47:17.646
But that's OK.

47:17.760 --> 47:19.922
Because if anyone puts
two and two together...

47:20.040 --> 47:21.246
That wasn't us.

47:21.360 --> 47:22.930
- (CHUCKLES)
